{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01T4e7aEr4VPU22DoigxLuEW","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"phase\": \"question\",\n3\t  \"questions\": [\n4\t    {\n5\t      \"id\": \"q1\",\n6\t      \"question\": \"Should src/config.py use python-dotenv for .env file loading, or a stdlib-only approach (manually parsing the file)? The project has no requirements.txt or pyproject.toml, and no existing dotenv dependency.\",\n7\t      \"category\": \"design\",\n8\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"Using python-dotenv is the standard approach but introduces an external dependency with no existing dependency management in place. A stdlib-only parser avoids that but is less robust.\"\n9\t    },\n10\t    {\n11\t      \"id\": \"q2\",\n12\t      \"question\": \"The task says 'src/config.py' but the main backend already lives in backend/ and has its own backend/inference/config.py. Is src/ the correct location, or should this go in backend/?\",\n13\t      \"category\": \"codebase\",\n14\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"Placing a config loader in src/ when all existing Python backend code lives in backend/ could create a disjointed layout. However, src/ already has greeting.py from a prior task, suggesting it may be a separate module area.\"\n15\t    },\n16\t    {\n17\t      \"id\": \"q3\",\n18\t      \"question\": \"The existing backend/server.py reads env vars directly via os.environ.get(). Should load_config() integrate with or remain independent of that pattern?\",\n19\t      \"category\": \"codebase\",\n20\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"If this config module is meant to eventually replace the scattered os.environ.get() calls in server.py, the interface matters. If it's standalone, the design is simpler.\"\n21\t    },\n22\t    {\n23\t      \"id\": \"q4\",\n24\t      \"question\": \"Should DEBUG be parsed as a boolean from string env var values (e.g., 'true', '1', 'yes') and if so, which values should be truthy? The backend already has a _read_bool_e